Goodness of Fit VS Predictive Power?

\[ \begin{equation} \nonumber y_i = f(x_i) + \epsilon_i \end{equation} \]

with \(\epsilon_i\) random noise.

How can we find \(f(x_{1,i},x_{2,i}, ..., x_{k,i})\) for a certain covariates matrix X in the information set?

Minimize the error?

\[ \begin{equation} \nonumber \hat{f}(X_i) = \underset{f}{\operatorname{argmin}} E[(y_i - f(X_i))^2] ? \end{equation} \]

One possible solution is to find the argument that minimize the sum of squared residuals, assuming that the predictor belong to a certain class of function (e.g.linear).

Or maybe

(\(\textbf{Y}_i, \textbf{X}_i\)) are future observations.

\[ \begin{equation} \nonumber E[(\textbf{Y}_i - \hat{f}(\textbf{X}_i))^2] = E[(y_i - \hat{f}(X_i))^2] + g(\epsilon_i) \end{equation} \]

Is \(g(\epsilon_i) = 0\) ?

Efron (2004):

The assessment of predictive accuracy is a form of bias estimation: ERR, the apparent error, is downward biased for the true predictive error.

\(g(\epsilon_i) > 0\) \(\forall \hat{f}\) (and most of the loss functions).

Overfitting VS Underfitting


  • Overfitting occurs when a statistical model or machine learning algorithm captures the noise of the data.
  • Underfitting occurs when the model does not capture the trend of the data.

Overfitting occurs when the model is too flexible, capturing too much in-sample variance. It usually leads to:

  • High Mean Squared Prediction Error (MSE on new observations).
  • Low Mean Squared Error on the training data.

The Bias-Variance trade off


\[ \begin{equation} E[(Y - \hat{f}(x))^2] = \sigma_\epsilon^2 + Var(\hat{f}(x)) + E[f(x) - E[\hat{f}(x)]]^2 \end{equation} \]

The results come from the fact that \(Var(Z) = E[Z^2] - E[Z]^2\).

The first term of the equation is random noise. The second term is the variance of the estimator and the last term is the bias squared.


  • Low Bias \(\rightarrow\) high flexibility \(\rightarrow\) high variance
  • Low Variance \(\rightarrow\) low flexibility \(\rightarrow\) high bias


Complexity and bias-variance trade-off

How to compute the MSPE?

  • Test-Training Set
  • K fold Cross Validation
  • Leave one out Cross Validation

Test-Training Set:

  • Divide the data in two subsets
  • Use one of them (training set) to build the model
  • Make predictions in the other set

Example - Practice

Data Generating Process:

For this example we generate 20 input variables, independently and uniformly distributed between -30 and 30. Then, we construct a dependent variable such that y \(\sim\) 3 + 5*V20 and we add some random noise.

## Generate a set of input variable

set.seed(123)
n <- 100
p <-  20
x <- matrix(runif(n*p, min=-30,max=30), n , p)

## Generate the output variable as a linear combination of x

## With jitter() you add random noise
y <-  jitter(3 + 5*x[,20], factor=10000)

## Look at the relationship

plot(cbind(x[,20],y))

## Construct a linear model with all the variables

full <- lm(y~x) ## All variables
null <- lm(y~1) ## No variables

truth <- lm(y~x[,20]) ## true relationship

## Evaluate the MSE of each model


mse1 <- mean((y-predict(full))^2)
mse2 <- mean((y-predict(null))^2)
mse3 <- mean((y-predict(truth))^2)

print(cbind(mse1,mse2,mse3))
##          mse1     mse2     mse3
## [1,] 12169.91 24196.81 14422.44
## See the behaviour of the mse in function of the number of variables

## store MSE, construct each regression on columns of X

mse <- rep(NA, length=20)
for (i in 1:20){ 
  data <- x[,c(1:i)]
  reg <- lm(y~data)
  mse[i] <- mean((y-predict(reg))^2)
  
}

plot(cbind(c(1:20), mse),  type="n", main="MSE VS Number of Variables", xlab="Number of Variables")

lines(cbind(c(1:20), mse), col="purple", lwd=3)

## Repeat the process but now with a test and training set



set.seed(123)

## Pick randomly 1/5th of observastions
ii <- sample(nrow(x), floor(nrow(x)/5))

## Built a test and training set

data.te <- x[ii, ]
data.tr <- x[-ii,]
y.te <- y[ii]
y.tr <- y[-ii]


full <- lm(y.tr~data.tr) ## All variables
null <- lm(y.tr~1) ## No variables

truth <- lm(y.tr~data.tr[,20]) ## true relationship

## Evaluate the MSE of each model (again)


mspe1 <- mean((y.te-predict(full, newx=data.te))^2)
mspe2 <- mean((y.te-predict(null, newx= data.te))^2)
mspe3 <- mean((y.te-predict(truth, newx=data.te))^2)

print(cbind(mspe1,mspe2,mspe3))
##         mspe1    mspe2    mspe3
## [1,] 32426.17 20267.25 30691.77
## Compare
print(cbind(mse1,mse2,mse3))
##          mse1     mse2     mse3
## [1,] 12169.91 24196.81 14422.44
## store MSE, construct each regression on columns of X

mspe <- rep(NA, length=20)
for (i in 1:20){ 
  data <- data.tr[,c(1:i)]
  reg <- lm(y.tr~data)
  mspe[i] <- mean((y.te-predict(reg, newx = data.te[,c(1:i)]))^2)
  
}



plot(cbind(c(1:20), mspe),  type="n", main="MSPE", xlab="Number of Variables", ylab="MSPE")

lines(cbind(c(1:20), mspe), col="blue", lwd=3)

The trade-off between the number of observations in test and traning set:

  • The more the observations in the test set, the lower the variance of the MSPE, but the higher the bias
  • The more the observations in the training set, the lower the bias, but the higher the variance of the MSPE


Could you tell why?

K-folds Cross Validation

  • Divide randomly the observations in k folds
  • Use k-1 folds as a training set
  • Make the predictions and compute the MSPE on the remaining fold
  • Repeat the process for each fold
  • Use the mean of each MSE as an estimator of the MSPE


Leave-one-out Cross-Validation:

  • Use n-1 observations as a training set
  • Make the predictions and compute the MSPE on the remaining observation
  • Repeat the process n times
  • Use the mean of each MSE as an estimator of the MSPE

Leave-one-out Cross-Validation has the highest variance but the lowest bias. It is a valid alternative to K-folds when cross validation is computational intensive:

\[ \begin{equation} GCV(\hat{Y}) = \frac{1}{N}{\frac{\sum (y_i - \hat{f}(x_i))}{(1 - trace(S)/N)}} \end{equation} \]

Where \(\hat{Y} = SY\) , S is the regression matrix and it is independent on Y. \

Generally we will use K-folds Cross Validation.

CV: Example

forestfires <- read.csv("./data/forestfires.csv")

n <- nrow(forestfires)
k <- 5
set.seed(123)
y <- forestfires$area
ii <- sample(rep(1:k, length= n))
pr1 <- pr2  <- array(0, k)
mspe1 <- mspe2 <- array(0, k)

  for (j in 1:k){
    hold <- (ii == j)
    train <- (ii != j)
    
    reg2 <- lm(area~temp+day+wind+rain, data=forestfires[train,]) 
    reg1 <- lm(area~temp, data=forestfires[train,] ) 
    
    pr1[hold] <- predict(reg2, newdata= forestfires[hold,]) 
    pr2[hold] <- predict(reg1, newdata= forestfires[hold,]) 
    
  mspe1[j] <- mean((pr1 - y)^2, na.rm = TRUE)
  mspe2[j] <- mean((pr2 - y)^2, na.rm = TRUE)
}

Solutions

wine.white <- read.table("./data/wine-white.txt")


names(wine.white)
##  [1] "fixed.acidity"        "volatile.acidity"     "citric.acid"         
##  [4] "residual.sugar"       "chlorides"            "free.sulfur.dioxide" 
##  [7] "total.sulfur.dioxide" "density"              "pH"                  
## [10] "sulphates"            "alcohol"              "quality"
n <- nrow(wine.white)
k <- 10
y <- wine.white$quality
ii <- sample(rep(1:k, length= n))
pr1 <- pr2 <-  pr3 <- numeric(length(y))
set.seed(123)

for (j in 1:k){
  hold <- (ii == j)
  train <- (ii != j)
  
  reg1 <- lm(quality~., data=wine.white[train,]) 
  reg2 <- lm(quality~pH+sulphates, data=wine.white[train,] ) 
  reg3 <- lm(quality~pH+sulphates+density+chlorides, data=wine.white[train,] )
  
  
  pr1[hold] <- predict(reg1, newdata= wine.white[hold,]) 
  pr2[hold] <- predict(reg2, newdata= wine.white[hold,])
  pr3[hold] <- predict(reg3, newdata= wine.white[hold,])}

mean((pr1 - y)^2)
## [1] 0.5696653
mean((pr2 - y)^2)
## [1] 0.7761307
mean((pr3 - y)^2)
## [1] 0.6908628
## To be more accurate we repeat this process 50 times (bootstrap the MSPE)


set.seed(123)

c <- 5
mspe1 <- mspe2 <- mspe3 <- c
for( i in 1: c){
  ii <- sample(ii)
  pr1 <- pr2 <-  pr3 <- numeric(length(y))
for (j in 1:k){
  hold <- (ii == j)
  train <- (ii != j)
  
  reg1 <- lm(quality~., data=wine.white[train,]) 
  reg2 <- lm(quality~pH+sulphates, data=wine.white[train,] ) 
  reg3 <- lm(quality~pH+sulphates+density+chlorides, data=wine.white[train,] )
  
  
  pr1[hold] <- predict(reg1, newdata= wine.white[hold,]) 
  pr2[hold] <- predict(reg2, newdata= wine.white[hold,])
  pr3[hold] <- predict(reg3, newdata= wine.white[hold,])}

mspe1[i] <- mean((pr1 - y)^2)
mspe2[i] <- mean((pr2 - y)^2)
mspe3[i] <- mean((pr3 - y)^2)
}

print(cbind(mean(mspe1),mean(mspe2),mean(mspe3)))
##           [,1]      [,2]      [,3]
## [1,] 0.5685367 0.7763299 0.6911663
